  "The term 'gibbous' comes from the Latin word for 'humpbacked' and describes a lunar phase where more than half but not all of the Moon's visible surface is illuminated. It applies to both waxing gibbous and waning gibbous phases.": "",
  "What is the synodic period of the Moon?": "",
  "The time it takes the Moon to rotate once on its axis": "",
  "The time between two successive identical phases of the Moon, about 29.5 days": "",
  "The time it takes for a lunar eclipse to complete": "",
  "The distance between the Moon and Earth at its closest point": "",
  "The synodic period is the time interval between two consecutive occurrences of the same lunar phase (e.g., new moon to new moon), approximately 29.5 days. It differs from the sidereal period because Earth is also moving in its orbit around the Sun.": "",
  "What is the corona in the context of a solar eclipse?": "",
