  "The outermost layer of the Sun's atmosphere, visible during a total solar eclipse": "",
  "The corona is the Sun's outermost atmospheric layer, consisting of extremely hot but very thin plasma. It is normally invisible due to the Sun's brightness, but during a total solar eclipse it becomes visible as a pearly white halo surrounding the darkened Sun.": "",
  "A student looks at the Moon and sees the right half illuminated while the left half is dark. The illuminated portion appears to be getting larger each night. Which phase is the Moon currently in?": "",
  "Waning crescent": "",
  "First quarter (waxing)": "",
  "In the Northern Hemisphere, when the right half of the Moon is lit and growing brighter, the Moon is at or near its first quarter phase. The waxing pattern means the illuminated area is increasing from right to left.": "",
  "During a field trip, students observe a total solar eclipse. Their teacher warns them never to look directly at the Sun during the partial phases but says it is safe to briefly view the total phase with the unaided eye. Why is the total phase safer to view?": "",
  "The Moon absorbs ultraviolet radiation during the eclipse": "",
