  "Lunar eclipses last longer so more people have time to see them": "",
  "Earth's shadow is much larger than the Moon, so during a lunar eclipse the entire Moon enters Earth's shadow and can be seen by anyone on the night side. The Moon's shadow on Earth is relatively small (about 270 km wide at most), creating a narrow path of totality for solar eclipses.": "",
  "A fisherman has heard that tides are strongest during new and full moons. What is the scientific explanation for this observation?": "",
